# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rabin-karp-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A **hash function** is any function that can be used to map data of arbitrary size to fixed-size values, though there are some hash functions that support variable-length output.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The values returned by a hash function are called *hash values*, *hash codes*, (*hash/message*) *digests*, or simply *hashes*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The values are usually used to index a fixed-size table called a *hash table*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Use of a hash function to index a hash table is called *hashing* or *scatter-storage addressing*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions and their associated hash tables are used in data storage and retrieval applications to access data in a small and nearly constant time per retrieval.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] They require an amount of storage space only fractionally greater than the total space required for the data or records themselves.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hashing is a way to access data quickly and efficiently.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Unlike lists or trees, it provides near-constant access time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] It also uses much less storage than trying to store all possible keys directly, especially when keys are large or variable in length.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Use of hash functions relies on statistical properties of key and function interaction: worst-case behavior is intolerably bad but rare, and average-case behavior can be nearly optimal (minimal collision).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions are related to (and often confused with) checksums, check digits, fingerprints, lossy compression, randomization functions, error-correcting codes, and ciphers.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Although the concepts overlap to some extent, each one has its own uses and requirements and is designed and optimized differently.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The hash function differs from these concepts mainly in terms of data integrity.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash tables may use non-cryptographic hash functions, while cryptographic hash functions are used in cybersecurity to secure sensitive data such as passwords.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In a hash table, a hash function takes a key as an input, which is associated with a datum or record and used to identify it to the data storage and retrieval application.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The keys may be fixed-length, like an integer, or variable-length, like a name.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In some cases, the key is the datum itself.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The output is a hash code used to index a hash table holding the data or records, or pointers to them.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A good hash function satisfies two basic properties: it should be very fast to compute, and it should minimize duplication of output values (collisions).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions rely on generating favorable probability distributions for their effectiveness, reducing access time to nearly constant.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] High table loading factors, pathological key sets, and poorly designed hash functions can result in access times approaching linear in the number of items in the table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions can be designed to give the best worst-case performance, good performance under high table loading factors, and in special cases, perfect (collisionless) mapping of keys into hash codes.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Implementation is based on parity-preserving bit operations (XOR and ADD), multiply, or divide.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A necessary adjunct to the hash function is a collision-resolution method that employs an auxiliary data structure like linked lists, or systematic probing of the table to find an empty slot.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions are used in conjunction with hash tables to store and retrieve data items or data records.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The hash function translates the key associated with each datum or record into a hash code, which is used to index the hash table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] When an item is to be added to the table, the hash code may index an empty slot (also called a bucket), in which case the item is added to the table there.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If the hash code indexes a full slot, then some kind of collision resolution is required: the new item may be omitted (not added to the table), or replace the old item, or be added to the table in some other location by a specified procedure.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] That procedure depends on the structure of the hash table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In *chained hashing*, each slot is the head of a linked list or chain, and items that collide at the slot are added to the chain.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Chains may be kept in random order and searched linearly, or in serial order, or as a self-ordering list by frequency to speed up access.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In *open address hashing*, the table is probed starting from the occupied slot in a specified manner, usually by linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing until an open slot is located or the entire table is probed (overflow).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Searching for the item follows the same procedure until the item is located, an open slot is found, or the entire table has been searched (item not in table).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions are also used to build caches for large data sets stored in slow media.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A cache is generally simpler than a hashed search table, since any collision can be resolved by discarding or writing back the older of the two colliding items.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions are an essential ingredient of the Bloom filter, a space-efficient probabilistic data structure that is used to test whether an element is a member of a set.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A special case of hashing is known as geometric hashing or the *grid method*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In these applications, the set of all inputs is some sort of metric space, and the hashing function can be interpreted as a partition of that space into a grid of *cells*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The table is often an array with two or more indices (called a *grid file*, *grid index*, *bucket grid*, and similar names), and the hash function returns an index tuple.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash tables are also used to implement associative arrays and dynamic sets.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A good hash function should map the expected inputs as evenly as possible over its output range.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] That is, every hash value in the output range should be generated with roughly the same probability.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The reason for this requirement is that the cost of hashing-based methods goes up sharply as the number of *collisions* — pairs of inputs that are mapped to the same hash value — increases.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If some hash values are more likely to occur than others, then a larger fraction of the lookup operations will have to search through a larger set of colliding table entries.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This criterion only requires the value to be *uniformly distributed*, not *random* in any sense.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A good randomizing function is (barring computational efficiency concerns) generally a good choice as a hash function, but the converse need not be true.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash tables often contain only a small subset of the valid inputs.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For instance, a club membership list may contain only a hundred or so member names, out of the very large set of all possible names.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In these cases, the uniformity criterion should hold for almost all typical subsets of entries that may be found in the table, not just for the global set of all possible entries.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In other words, if a typical set of *m* records is hashed to *n* table slots, then the probability of a bucket receiving many more than *m*/*n* records should be vanishingly small.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In particular, if *m* < *n*, then very few buckets should have more than one or two records.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A small number of collisions is virtually inevitable, even if *n* is much larger than *m*—see the birthday problem.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In special cases when the keys are known in advance and the key set is static, a hash function can be found that achieves absolute (or collisionless) uniformity.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Such a hash function is said to be *perfect*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] There is no algorithmic way of constructing such a function—searching for one is a factorial function of the number of keys to be mapped versus the number of table slots that they are mapped into.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] When testing a hash function, the uniformity of the distribution of hash values can be evaluated by the chi-squared test.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This test is a goodness-of-fit measure: it is the actual distribution of items in buckets versus the expected (or uniform) distribution of items.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] where n is the number of keys, m is the number of buckets, and *b**j* is the number of items in bucket j.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A ratio within one confidence interval (such as 0.95 to 1.05) is indicative that the hash function evaluated has an expected uniform distribution.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions can have some technical properties that make it more likely that they will have a uniform distribution when applied.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] One is the strict avalanche criterion: whenever a single input bit is complemented, each of the output bits changes with a 50% probability.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The reason for this property is that selected subsets of the keyspace may have low variability.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For the output to be uniformly distributed, a low amount of variability, even one bit, should translate into a high amount of variability (i.e. distribution over the tablespace) in the output.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Each bit should change with a probability of 50% because, if some bits are reluctant to change, then the keys become clustered around those values.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If the bits want to change too readily, then the mapping is approaching a fixed XOR function of a single bit.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Standard tests for this property have been described in the literature.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The relevance of the criterion to a multiplicative hash function is assessed here.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In data storage and retrieval applications, the use of a hash function is a trade-off between search time and data storage space.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If search time were unbounded, then a very compact unordered linear list would be the best medium; if storage space were unbounded, then a randomly accessible structure indexable by the key-value would be very large and very sparse, but very fast.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash function takes a finite amount of time to map a potentially large keyspace to a feasible amount of storage space searchable in a bounded amount of time regardless of the number of keys.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In most applications, the hash function should be computable with minimum latency and secondarily in a minimum number of instructions.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Computational complexity varies with the number of instructions required and latency of individual instructions, with the simplest being the bitwise methods (folding), followed by the multiplicative methods, and the most complex (slowest) are the division-based methods.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Because collisions should be infrequent, and cause a marginal delay but are otherwise harmless, it is usually preferable to choose a faster hash function over one that needs more computation but saves a few collisions.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Division-based implementations can be of particular concern because a division requires multiple cycles on nearly all processor microarchitectures.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Division (modulo) by a constant can be inverted to become a multiplication by the word-size multiplicative-inverse of that constant.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This can be done by the programmer, or by the compiler.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Division can also be reduced directly into a series of shift-subtracts and shift-adds, though minimizing the number of such operations required is a daunting problem; the number of machine-language instructions resulting may be more than a dozen and swamp the pipeline.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If the microarchitecture has hardware multiply functional units, then the multiply-by-inverse is likely a better approach.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] We can allow the table size *n* to not be a power of 2 and still not have to perform any remainder or division operation, as these computations are sometimes costly.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, let *n* be significantly less than 2*b*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Consider a pseudorandom number generator function *P*(key) that is uniform on the interval [0, 2*b* − 1].
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash function uniform on the interval [0, *n* − 1] is *n* *P*(key) / 2*b*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] We can replace the division by a (possibly faster) right bit shift: *n P*(key) >> *b*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If keys are being hashed repeatedly, and the hash function is costly, then computing time can be saved by precomputing the hash codes and storing them with the keys.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Matching hash codes almost certainly means that the keys are identical.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This technique is used for the transposition table in game-playing programs, which stores a 64-bit hashed representation of the board position.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A *universal hashing* scheme is a randomized algorithm that selects a hash function *h* among a family of such functions, in such a way that the probability of a collision of any two distinct keys is 1/*m*, where *m* is the number of distinct hash values desired—independently of the two keys.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Universal hashing ensures (in a probabilistic sense) that the hash function application will behave as well as if it were using a random function, for any distribution of the input data.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] It will, however, have more collisions than perfect hashing and may require more operations than a special-purpose hash function.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash function that allows only certain table sizes or strings only up to a certain length, or cannot accept a seed (i.e. allow double hashing) is less useful than one that does.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash function is applicable in a variety of situations.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash procedure must be deterministic—for a given input value, it must always generate the same hash value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In other words, it must be a function of the data to be hashed, in the mathematical sense of the term.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This requirement excludes hash functions that depend on external variable parameters, such as pseudo-random number generators or the time of day.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] It also excludes functions that depend on the memory address of the object being hashed, because the address may change during execution (as may happen on systems that use certain methods of garbage collection), although sometimes rehashing of the item is possible.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The determinism is in the context of the reuse of the function.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, Python adds the feature that hash functions make use of a randomized seed that is generated once when the Python process starts in addition to the input to be hashed.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The Python hash (SipHash) is still a valid hash function when used within a single run, but if the values are persisted (for example, written to disk), they can no longer be treated as valid hash values, since in the next run the random value might differ.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] It is often desirable that the output of a hash function have fixed size (but see below).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If, for example, the output is constrained to 32-bit integer values, then the hash values can be used to index into an array.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Such hashing is commonly used to accelerate data searches.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Producing fixed-length output from variable-length input can be accomplished by breaking the input data into chunks of specific size.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Hash functions used for data searches use some arithmetic expression that iteratively processes chunks of the input (such as the characters in a string) to produce the hash value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In many applications, the range of hash values may be different for each run of the program or may change along the same run (for instance, when a hash table needs to be expanded).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In those situations, one needs a hash function which takes two parameters—the input data *z*, and the number *n* of allowed hash values.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A common solution is to compute a fixed hash function with a very large range (say, 0 to 232 − 1), divide the result by *n*, and use the division's remainder.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If *n* is itself a power of 2, this can be done by bit masking and bit shifting.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] When this approach is used, the hash function must be chosen so that the result has fairly uniform distribution between 0 and *n* − 1, for any value of *n* that may occur in the application.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Depending on the function, the remainder may be uniform only for certain values of *n*, e.g. odd or prime numbers.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] When the hash function is used to store values in a hash table that outlives the run of the program, and the hash table needs to be expanded or shrunk, the hash table is referred to as a dynamic hash table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash function that will relocate the minimum number of records when the table is resized is desirable.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] What is needed is a hash function *H*(*z*,*n*) (where *z* is the key being hashed and *n* is the number of allowed hash values) such that *H*(*z*,*n* + 1) = *H*(*z*,*n*) with probability close to *n*/(*n* + 1).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Linear hashing and spiral hashing are examples of dynamic hash functions that execute in constant time but relax the property of uniformity to achieve the minimal movement property.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Extendible hashing uses a dynamic hash function that requires space proportional to *n* to compute the hash function, and it becomes a function of the previous keys that have been inserted.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Several algorithms that preserve the uniformity property but require time proportional to *n* to compute the value of *H*(*z*,*n*) have been invented.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash function with minimal movement is especially useful in distributed hash tables.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In some applications, the input data may contain features that are irrelevant for comparison purposes.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, when looking up a personal name, it may be desirable to ignore the distinction between upper and lower case letters.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For such data, one must use a hash function that is compatible with the data equivalence criterion being used: that is, any two inputs that are considered equivalent must yield the same hash value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This can be accomplished by normalizing the input before hashing it, as by upper-casing all letters.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] There are several common algorithms for hashing integers.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The method giving the best distribution is data-dependent.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] One of the simplest and most common methods in practice is the modulo division method.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If the data to be hashed is small enough, then one can use the data itself (reinterpreted as an integer) as the hashed value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The cost of computing this *identity* hash function is effectively zero.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This hash function is perfect, as it maps each input to a distinct hash value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The meaning of "small enough" depends on the size of the type that is used as the hashed value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, in Java, the hash code is a 32-bit integer.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Thus the 32-bit integer `Integer` and 32-bit floating-point `Float` objects can simply use the value directly, whereas the 64-bit integer `Long` and 64-bit floating-point `Double` cannot.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Other types of data can also use this hashing scheme.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, when mapping character strings between upper and lower case, one can use the binary encoding of each character, interpreted as an integer, to index a table that gives the alternative form of that character ("A" for "a", "8" for "8", etc.).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If each character is stored in 8 bits (as in extended ASCII or ISO Latin 1), the table has only 28 = 256 entries; in the case of Unicode characters, the table would have 17 × 216 = 1114112 entries.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The same technique can be used to map two-letter country codes like "us" or "za" to country names (262 = 676 table entries), 5-digit ZIP codes like 13083 to city names (100000 entries), etc.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Invalid data values (such as the country code "xx" or the ZIP code 00000) may be left undefined in the table or mapped to some appropriate "null" value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If the keys are uniformly or sufficiently uniformly distributed over the key space, so that the key values are essentially random, then they may be considered to be already "hashed".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In this case, any number of any bits in the key may be extracted and collated as an index into the hash table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, a simple hash function might mask off the m least significant bits and use the result as an index into a hash table of size 2*m*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A mid-squares hash code is produced by squaring the input and extracting an appropriate number of middle digits or bits.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, if the input is 123456789 and the hash table size 10000, then squaring the key produces 15241578750190521, so the hash code is taken as the middle 4 digits of the 17-digit number (ignoring the high digit) 8750.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The mid-squares method produces a reasonable hash code if there is not a lot of leading or trailing zeros in the key.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This is a variant of multiplicative hashing, but not as good because an arbitrary key is not a good multiplier.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A standard technique is to use a modulo function on the key, by selecting a divisor M which is a prime number close to the table size, so *h*(*K*) ≡ *K* (mod *M*).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This gives a distribution from {0, *M* − 1}.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This gives good results over a large number of key sets.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A significant drawback of division hashing is that division requires multiple cycles on most modern architectures (including x86) and can be 10 times slower than multiplication.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A second drawback is that it will not break up clustered keys.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This technique works well in practice because many key sets are sufficiently random already, and the probability that a key set will be cyclical by a large prime number is small.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Algebraic coding is a variant of the division method of hashing which uses division by a polynomial modulo 2 instead of an integer to map n bits to m bits.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If *Z*(*x*) is constructed to have t or fewer non-zero coefficients, then keys which share fewer than t bits are guaranteed to not collide.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Z is a function of k, t, and n (the last of which is a divisor of 2*k* − 1) and is constructed from the finite field GF(2*k*).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Define $P(x)=\prod _{j\in S}(x-\alpha ^{j})$ where α ∈*n* GF(2*k*) and where the coefficients of *P*(*x*) are computed in this field.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Since α2*j* is a root of *P*(*x*) whenever α*j* is a root, it follows that the coefficients *pi* of *P*(*x*) satisfy *p*2 *i* = *p*i, so they are all 0 or 1.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If *R*(*x*) = *r**n*−1*x**n*−1 + ⋯ + *r*1*x* + *r*0 is any nonzero polynomial modulo 2 with at most t nonzero coefficients, then *R*(*x*) is not a multiple of *P*(*x*) modulo 2.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If follows that the corresponding hash function will map keys with fewer than t bits in common to unique indices.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The usual outcome is that either n will get large, or t will get large, or both, for the scheme to be computationally feasible.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Therefore, it is more suited to hardware or microcode implementation.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Unique permutation hashing has a guaranteed best worst-case insertion time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Standard multiplicative hashing uses the formula *h**a*(*K*) = ⌊(*aK* mod *W*) / (*W*/*M*)⌋, which produces a hash value in {0, …, *M* − 1}.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The value a is an appropriately chosen value that should be relatively prime to W; it should be large, and its binary representation a random mix of 1s and 0s.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] An important practical special case occurs when *W* = 2*w* and *M* = 2*m* are powers of 2 and w is the machine word size.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] and for fixed m and w this translates into a single integer multiplication and right-shift, making it one of the fastest hash functions to compute.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Multiplicative hashing is susceptible to a "common mistake" that leads to poor diffusion—higher-value input bits do not affect lower-value output bits.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A transmutation on the input which shifts the span of retained top bits down and XORs or ADDs them to the key before the multiplication step corrects for this.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Fibonacci hashing is a form of multiplicative hashing in which the multiplier is 2*w* / ϕ, where w is the machine word length and ϕ (phi) is the golden ratio (approximately 1.618).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A property of this multiplier is that it uniformly distributes over the table space, blocks of consecutive keys with respect to any block of bits in the key.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Consecutive keys within the high bits or low bits of the key (or some other field) are relatively common.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The multiplier should be odd, so the least significant bit of the output is invertible modulo 2*w*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The last two values given above are rounded (up and down, respectively) by more than 1/2 of a least-significant bit to achieve this.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Zobrist hashing was originally introduced as a means of compactly representing chess positions in computer game-playing programs.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A unique random number was assigned to represent each type of piece (six each for black and white) on each space of the board.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Thus a table of 64×12 such numbers is initialized at the start of the program.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The random numbers could be any length, but 64 bits was natural due to the 64 squares on the board.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A position was transcribed by cycling through the pieces in a position, indexing the corresponding random numbers (vacant spaces were not included in the calculation) and XORing them together (the starting value could be 0 (the identity value for XOR) or a random seed).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The resulting value was reduced by modulo, folding, or some other operation to produce a hash table index.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The original Zobrist hash was stored in the table as the representation of the position.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Later, the method was extended to hashing integers by representing each byte in each of 4 possible positions in the word by a unique 32-bit random number.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Thus, a table of 28×4 random numbers is constructed.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A 32-bit hashed integer is transcribed by successively indexing the table with the value of each byte of the plain text integer and XORing the loaded values together (again, the starting value can be the identity value or a random seed).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The natural extension to 64-bit integers is by use of a table of 28×8 64-bit random numbers.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This kind of function has some nice theoretical properties, one of which is called *3-tuple independence*, meaning that every 3-tuple of keys is equally likely to be mapped to any 3-tuple of hash values.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A hash function can be designed to exploit existing entropy in the keys.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] If the keys have leading or trailing zeros, or particular fields that are unused, always zero or some other constant, or generally vary little, then masking out only the volatile bits and hashing on those will provide a better and possibly faster hash function.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Selected divisors or multipliers in the division and multiplicative schemes may make more uniform hash functions if the keys are cyclic or have other redundancies.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] When the data values are long (or variable-length) character strings—such as personal names, web page addresses, or mail messages—their distribution is usually very uneven, with complicated dependencies.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, text in any natural language has highly non-uniform distributions of characters, and character pairs, characteristic of the language.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For such data, it is prudent to use a hash function that depends on all characters of the string—and depends on each character in a different way.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Simplistic hash functions may add the first and last *n* characters of a string along with the length, or form a word-size hash from the middle 4 characters of a string.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This saves iterating over the (potentially long) string, but hash functions that do not hash on all characters of a string can readily become linear due to redundancies, clustering, or other pathologies in the key set.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Such strategies may be effective as a custom hash function if the structure of the keys is such that either the middle, ends, or other fields are zero or some other invariant constant that does not differentiate the keys; then the invariant parts of the keys can be ignored.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The paradigmatic example of folding by characters is to add up the integer values of all the characters in the string.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A better idea is to multiply the hash total by a constant, typically a sizable prime number, before adding in the next character, ignoring overflow.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Using exclusive-or instead of addition is also a plausible alternative.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The final operation would be a modulo, mask, or other function to reduce the word value to an index the size of the table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The weakness of this procedure is that information may cluster in the upper or lower bits of the bytes; this clustering will remain in the hashed result and cause more collisions than a proper randomizing hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] ASCII byte codes, for example, have an upper bit of 0, and printable strings do not use the last byte code or most of the first 32 byte codes, so the information, which uses the remaining byte codes, is clustered in the remaining bits in an unobvious manner.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The classic approach, dubbed the PJW hash based on the work of Peter J.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Weinberger at Bell Labs in the 1970s, was originally designed for hashing identifiers into compiler symbol tables as given in the "Dragon Book".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This hash function offsets the bytes 4 bits before adding them together.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] When the quantity wraps, the high 4 bits are shifted out and if non-zero, xored back into the low byte of the cumulative quantity.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The result is a word-size hash code to which a modulo or other reducing operation can be applied to produce the final hash index.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Today, especially with the advent of 64-bit word sizes, much more efficient variable-length string hashing by word chunks is available.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The final word, which may have unoccupied byte positions, is filled with zeros or a specified randomizing value before being folded into the hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The accumulated hash code is reduced by a final modulo or other operation to yield an index into the table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Analogous to the way an ASCII or EBCDIC character string representing a decimal number is converted to a numeric quantity for computing, a variable-length string can be converted as *x**k*−1a*k*−1 + *x**k*−2a*k*−2 + ⋯ + *x*1*a* + *x*0.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This is simply a polynomial in a radix *a* > 1 that takes the components (*x*0,*x*1,...,*x**k*−1) as the characters of the input string of length *k*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] It can be used directly as the hash code, or a hash function applied to it to map the potentially large value to the hash table size.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The value of *a* is usually a prime number large enough to hold the number of different characters in the character set of potential keys.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Radix conversion hashing of strings minimizes the number of collisions.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Available data sizes may restrict the maximum length of string that can be hashed with this method.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] For example, a 128-bit word will hash only a 26-character alphabetic string (ignoring case) with a radix of 29; a printable ASCII string is limited to 9 characters using radix 97 and a 64-bit word.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] However, alphabetic keys are usually of modest length, because keys must be stored in the hash table.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Numeric character strings are usually not a problem; 64 bits can count up to 1019, or 19 decimal digits with radix 10.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] In some applications, such as substring search, one can compute a hash function *h* for every *k*-character substring of a given *n*-character string by advancing a window of width *k* characters along the string, where *k* is a fixed integer, and *n* > *k*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The straightforward solution, which is to extract such a substring at every character position in the text and compute *h* separately, requires a number of operations proportional to *k*·*n*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] However, with the proper choice of *h*, one can use the technique of rolling hash to compute all those hashes with an effort proportional to *mk* + *n* where *m* is the number of occurrences of the substring.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The hash function used for the algorithm is usually the Rabin fingerprint, designed to avoid collisions in 8-bit character strings, but other suitable hash functions are also used.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing, also known as similarity hashing, is a technique for detecting data that is similar, but not exactly the same, as other data.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hash functions, which are designed to have significantly different hashes for even minor differences.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Fuzzy hashing has been used to identify malware and has potential for other applications, like data loss prevention and detecting multiple versions of code.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Perceptual hashing is the use of a fingerprinting algorithm that produces a snippet, hash, or fingerprint of various forms of multimedia.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] A perceptual hash is a type of locality-sensitive hash, which is analogous if features of the multimedia are similar.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This is in contrast to cryptographic hashing, which relies on the avalanche effect of a small change in input value creating a drastic change in output value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Perceptual hash functions are widely used in finding cases of online copyright infringement as well as in digital forensics because of the ability to have a correlation between hashes so similar data can be found (for instance with a differing watermark).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] Worst case results for a hash function can be assessed two ways: theoretical and practical.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The theoretical worst case is the probability that all keys map to a single slot.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The practical worst case is the expected longest probe sequence (hash function + collision resolution method).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] This analysis considers uniform hashing, that is, any key will map to any particular slot with probability 1/*m*, a characteristic of universal hash functions.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] While Knuth worries about adversarial attack on real time systems, Gonnet has shown that the probability of such a case is "ridiculously small".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] His representation was that the probability of *k* of *n* keys mapping to a single slot is α*k* / (*e*α *k*!), where *α* is the load factor, *n*/*m*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/hash-function] The term *hash* offers a natural analogy with its non-technical meaning (to chop up or make a mess out of something), given how hash functions scramble their input data to derive their output.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and independently discovered by Donald Knuth "a few weeks later" from automata theory.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and Vaughan Pratt published a technical report in 1970.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The three also published the algorithm jointly in 1977.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Independently, in 1969, Matiyasevich discovered a similar algorithm, coded by a two-dimensional Turing machine, while studying a string-pattern-matching recognition problem over a binary alphabet.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This was the first linear-time algorithm for string matching.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A string-matching algorithm wants to find the starting index `m` in string `s` that matches the search word `w`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The most straightforward algorithm, known as the "brute-force" or "naive" algorithm, is to look for a word match at each index `m`, i.e. the position in the string being searched that corresponds to the character `s[m]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At each position `m` the algorithm first checks for equality of the first character in the word being searched, i.e.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a match is found, the algorithm tests the other characters in the word being searched by checking successive values of the word position index, `i`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm retrieves the character `w[i]` in the word being searched and checks for equality of the expression `S[m+i] =?
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If all successive characters match in `W` at position `m`, then a match is found at that position in the search string.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the index `m` reaches the end of the string then there is no match, in which case the search is said to "fail".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Usually, the trial check will quickly reject the trial match.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are uniformly distributed random letters, then the chance that characters match is 1 in 26.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In most cases, the trial check will reject the match at the initial letter.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The chance that the first two letters will match is 1 in 676 (1 in 26^2 chances of a match over 26 possible letters).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] So if the characters are random, then the expected complexity of searching string `s` of length *n* is on the order of *n* comparisons or *Θ*(*n*).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `s` is 1 million characters and `w` is 1000 characters, then the string search should complete after about 1.04 million character comparisons.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] That expected performance is not guaranteed.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are not random, then checking a trial `m` may take many character comparisons.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The worst case is if the two strings match in all but the last letter.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Imagine that the string `s` consists of 1 million characters that are all *A*, and that the word `w` is 999 *A* characters terminating in a final *B* character.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string-matching algorithm will now examine 1000 characters at each trial position before rejecting the match and advancing the trial position.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string search example would now take about 1000 character comparisons times 1 million positions for 1 billion character comparisons.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the length of `w` is *k*, then the worst-case performance is *O*(*k*⋅*n*).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The KMP algorithm has a better worst-case performance than the straightforward algorithm.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP spends a little time precomputing a table (on the order of the size of `w`, *O*(*k*)), and then it uses that table to do an efficient search of the string in *O*(*n*).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The difference is that KMP makes use of previous match information that the straightforward algorithm does not.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In the example above, when KMP sees a trial match fail on the 1000th character (`i` = 999) because `s[m + 999] ≠ w[999]`, it will increment `m` by 1, but it will know that the first 998 characters at the new position already match.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP matched 999 *A* characters before discovering a mismatch at the 1000th character (position 999).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Advancing the trial match position `m` by one throws away the first *A*, so KMP knows there are 998 *A* characters that match `w` and does not retest them; that is, KMP sets `i` to 998.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP maintains its knowledge in the precomputed table and two state variables.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] When KMP discovers a mismatch, the table determines how much KMP will increase (variable `m`) and where it will resume testing (variable `i`).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To illustrate the algorithm's details, consider a (relatively artificial) run of the algorithm, where `W` = "ABCDABD" and `S` = "ABC ABCDAB ABCDABCDABDE".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In each step the algorithm compares `S[m+i]` with `W[i]` and increments `i` if they are equal.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm compares successive characters of `W` to "parallel" characters of `S`, moving from one to the next by incrementing `i` if they match.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, in the fourth step `S[3] = ' '` does not match `W[3] = 'D'`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Rather than beginning to search again at `S[1]`, we note that no `'A'` occurs between positions 1 and 2 in `S`; hence, having checked all those characters previously (and knowing they matched the corresponding characters in `W`), there is no chance of finding the beginning of a match.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm sets `m = 3` and `i = 0`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here, `i` increments through a nearly complete match `"ABCDAB"` until `i = 6` giving a mismatch at `W[6]` and `S[10]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, just prior to the end of the current partial match, there was that substring `"AB"` that could be the beginning of a new match, so the algorithm must take this into consideration.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As these characters match the two characters prior to the current position, those characters need not be checked again; the algorithm sets `m = 8` (the start of the initial prefix) and `i = 2` (signaling the first two characters match) and continues matching.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the algorithm not only omits previously matched characters of `S` (the `"AB"`), but also previously matched characters of `W` (the prefix `"AB"`).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This search at the new position fails immediately because `W[2]` (a `'C'`) does not match `S[10]` (a `' '`).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As in the first trial, the mismatch causes the algorithm to return to the beginning of `W` and begins searching at the mismatched character position of `S`: `m = 10`, reset `i = 0`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The match at `m=10` fails immediately, so the algorithm next tries `m = 11` and `i = 0`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Once again, the algorithm matches `"ABCDAB"`, but the next character, `'C'`, does not match the final character `'D'` of the word `W`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Reasoning as before, the algorithm sets `m = 15`, to start at the two-character string `"AB"` leading up to the current position, set `i = 2`, and continue matching from the current position.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This time the match is complete, and the first character of the match is `S[15]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The above example contains all the elements of the algorithm.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] For the moment, we assume the existence of a "partial match" table `T`, described below, which indicates where we need to look for the start of a new match when a mismatch is found.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The entries of `T` are constructed so that if we have a match starting at `S[m]` that fails when comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match will start at index `m + i - T[i]` in `S` (that is, `T[i]` is the amount of "backtracking" we need to do after a mismatch).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The following is a sample pseudocode implementation of the KMP search algorithm.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Assuming the prior existence of the table `T`, the search portion of the Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm has complexity *O*(*n*), where *n* is the length of `S` and the *O* is big-O notation.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Except for the fixed overhead incurred in entering and exiting the function, all the computations are performed in the `**while**` loop.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To bound the number of iterations of this loop; observe that `T` is constructed so that if a match which had begun at `S[m]` fails while comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match must begin at `S[m + (i - T[i])]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In particular, the next possible match must occur at a higher index than `m`, so that `T[i] < i`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This fact implies that the loop can execute at most 2*n* times, since at each iteration it executes one of the two branches in the loop.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The first branch invariably increases `i` and does not change `m`, so that the index `m + i` of the currently scrutinized character of `S` is increased.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The second branch adds `i - T[i]` to `m`, and as we have seen, this is always a positive number.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the location `m` of the beginning of the current potential match is increased.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At the same time, the second branch leaves `m + i` unchanged, for `m` gets `i - T[i]` added to it, and immediately after `T[i]` gets assigned as the new value of `i`, hence `new_m + new_i = old_m + old_i - T[old_i] + T[old_i] = old_m + old_i`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the loop executes at most 2*n* times, showing that the time complexity of the search algorithm is *O*(*n*).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here is another way to think about the runtime: Let us say we begin to match `W` and `S` at position `i` and `p`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `W` exists as a substring of `S` at p, then `W[0..m] = S[p..p+m]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon success, that is, the word and the text matched at the positions (`W[i] = S[p+i]`), we increase `i` by 1.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon failure, that is, the word and the text do not match at the positions (`W[i] ≠ S[p+i]`), the text pointer is kept still, while the word pointer is rolled back a certain amount (`i = T[i]`, where `T` is the jump table), and we attempt to match `W[T[i]]` with `S[p+i]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The maximum number of roll-back of `i` is bounded by `i`, that is to say, for any failure, we can only roll back as much as we have progressed up to the failure.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The goal of the table is to allow the algorithm not to match any character of `S` more than once.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In other words, we "pre-search" the pattern itself and compile a list of all possible fallback positions that bypass a maximum of hopeless characters while not sacrificing any potential matches in doing so.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence `T[i]` is exactly the length of the longest possible *proper* initial segment of `W` which is also a segment of the substring ending at `W[i - 1]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We use the convention that the empty string has length 0.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since a mismatch at the very start of the pattern is a special case (there is no possibility of backtracking), we set `T[0] = -1`, as discussed below.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We consider the example of `W = "ABCDABD"` first.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We will see that it follows much the same pattern as the main search, and is efficient for similar reasons.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To find `T[1]`, we must discover a proper suffix of `"A"` which is also a prefix of pattern `W`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But there are no proper suffixes of `"A"`, so we set `T[1] = 0`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However "B" is not a prefix of the pattern `W`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Continuing to `T[3]`, we first check the proper suffix of length 1, and as in the previous case it fails.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence at each stage, the shortcut rule is that one needs to consider checking suffixes of a given size m+1 only if a valid suffix of size m was found at the previous stage (i.e.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `T[x] = m`) and should not bother to check m+2, m+3, etc.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, we need not even concern ourselves with substrings having length 2, and as in the previous case the sole one with length 1 fails, so `T[3] = 0`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We pass to the subsequent `W[4]`, `'A'`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The same logic shows that the longest substring we need to consider has length 1, and as in the previous case it fails since "D" is not a prefix of `W`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But instead of setting `T[4] = 0`, we can do better by noting that `W[4] = W[0]`, and also that a look-up of `T[4]` implies the corresponding `S` character, `S[m+4]`, was a mismatch and therefore `S[m+4] ≠ 'A'`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus there is no point in restarting the search at `S[m+4]`; we should begin at 1 position ahead.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This means that we may shift pattern `W` by match length plus one character, so `T[4] = -1`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Considering now the next character, `W[5]`, which is `'B'`: though by inspection the longest substring would appear to be `'A'`, we still set `T[5] = 0`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The reasoning is similar to why `T[4] = -1`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `W[5]` itself extends the prefix match begun with `W[4]`, and we can assume that the corresponding character in `S`, `S[m+5] ≠ 'B'`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Finally, we see that the next character in the ongoing segment starting at `W[4] = 'A'` would be `'B'`, and indeed this is also `W[5]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Furthermore, the same argument as above shows that we need not look before `W[4]` to find a segment for `W[6]`, so that this is it, and we take `T[6] = 2`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The example above illustrates the general technique for assembling the table with a minimum of fuss.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The principle is that of the overall search: most of the work was already done in getting to the current position, so very little needs to be done in leaving it.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The only minor complication is that the logic which is correct late in the string erroneously gives non-proper substrings at the beginning.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This necessitates some initialization code.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The time (and space) complexity of the table algorithm is $O(k)$ , where k is the length of `W`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Combined, the outer and inner loops take at most $2k-2$ iterations.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This corresponds to $O(k)$ time complexity using the Big O notation.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since the two portions of the algorithm have, respectively, complexities of `O(k)` and `O(n)`, the complexity of the overall algorithm is `O(n + k)`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] These complexities are independent of how many repetitive patterns are in `W` or `S`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] It is known that the delay, that is the number of times a symbol of the text is compared to symbols of the pattern, is less than $\lfloor \log _{\Phi }(k+1)\rfloor$ , where Φ is the golden ration $(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2$ .
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In 1993, an algorithm was given that has a delay bounded by $\min(1+\lfloor \log _{2}k\rfloor ,|\Sigma |)$ where Σ is the size of the alphabet (of the pattern).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A real-time version of KMP can be implemented using a separate failure function table for each character in the alphabet.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a mismatch occurs on character x in the text, the failure function table for character x is consulted for the index i in the pattern at which the mismatch took place.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This will return the length of the longest substring ending at i matching a prefix of the pattern, with the added condition that the character after the prefix is x .
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] With this restriction, character x in the text need not be checked again in the next phase, and so only a constant number of operations are executed between the processing of each index of the text.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This satisfies the real-time computing restriction.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Booth's algorithm uses a modified version of the KMP preprocessing function to find the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The failure function is progressively calculated as the string is rotated.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] The **Rabin fingerprinting scheme** (a.k.a.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] **Polynomial fingerprinting**) is a method for implementing fingerprints using polynomials over a finite field.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] Given an *n*-bit message *m*0,...,*m**n*-1, we view it as a polynomial of degree *n*-1 over the finite field GF(2).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] We then pick a random irreducible polynomial ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠ of degree *k* over GF(2), and we define the fingerprint of the message *m* to be the remainder $r(x)$ after division of $f(x)$ by $p(x)$ over GF(2) which can be viewed as a polynomial of degree *k* − 1 or as a *k*-bit number.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] Many implementations of the Rabin–Karp algorithm internally use Rabin fingerprints.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] The *Low Bandwidth Network Filesystem* (LBFS) from MIT uses Rabin fingerprints to implement variable size shift-resistant blocks.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] The basic idea is that the filesystem computes the cryptographic hash of each block in a file.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] To save on transfers between the client and server, they compare their checksums and only transfer blocks whose checksums differ.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] But one problem with this scheme is that a single insertion at the beginning of the file will cause every checksum to change if fixed-sized (e.g.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] So the idea is to select blocks not based on a specific offset but rather by some property of the block contents.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] LBFS does this by sliding a 48 byte window over the file and computing the Rabin fingerprint of each window.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] When the low 13 bits of the fingerprint are zero LBFS calls those 48 bytes a breakpoint and ends the current block and begins a new one.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] Since the output of Rabin fingerprints are pseudo-random the probability of any given 48 bytes being a breakpoint is $2^{-13}$ (1 in 8192).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] This has the effect of shift-resistant variable size blocks.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-fingerprint] Note that this is a problem similar to that faced by rsync.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] In computer science, the **Rabin–Karp algorithm** or **Karp–Rabin algorithm** is a string-searching algorithm created by Richard M.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Rabin (1987) that uses hashing to find an exact match of a pattern string in a text.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] It uses a rolling hash to quickly filter out positions of the text that cannot match the pattern, and then checks for a match at the remaining positions.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Generalizations of the same idea can be used to find more than one match of a single pattern, or to find matches for more than one pattern.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] To find a single match of a single pattern, the expected time of the algorithm is linear in the combined length of the pattern and text, although its worst-case time complexity is the product of the two lengths.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] To find multiple matches, the expected time is linear in the input lengths, plus the combined length of all the matches, which could be greater than linear.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] In contrast, the Aho–Corasick algorithm can find all matches of multiple patterns in worst-case time and space linear in the input length and the number of matches (instead of the total length of the matches).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] A practical application of the algorithm is detecting plagiarism.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Given source material, the algorithm can rapidly search through a paper for instances of sentences from the source material, ignoring details such as case and punctuation.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Because of the abundance of the sought strings, single-string searching algorithms are impractical.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] A naive string matching algorithm compares the given pattern against all positions in the given text.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Each comparison takes time proportional to the length of the pattern, and the number of positions is proportional to the length of the text.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Therefore, the worst-case time for such a method is proportional to the product of the two lengths.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] In many practical cases, this time can be significantly reduced by cutting short the comparison at each position as soon as a mismatch is found, but this idea cannot guarantee any speedup.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm instead achieves its speedup by using a hash function to quickly perform an approximate check for each position, and then only performing an exact comparison at the positions that pass this approximate check.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] A hash function is a function which converts every string into a numeric value, called its *hash value*; for example, we might have `hash("hello")=5`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] If two strings are equal, their hash values are also equal.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] For a well-designed hash function, the inverse is true, in an approximate sense: strings that are unequal are very unlikely to have equal hash values.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm proceeds by computing, at each position of the text, the hash value of a string starting at that position with the same length as the pattern.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] If this hash value equals the hash value of the pattern, it performs a full comparison at that position.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] In order for this to work well, the hash function should be selected randomly from a family of hash functions that are unlikely to produce many false positives, that is, positions of the text which have the same hash value as the pattern but do not actually match the pattern.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] These positions contribute to the running time of the algorithm unnecessarily, without producing a match.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Additionally, the hash function used should be a rolling hash, a hash function whose value can be quickly updated from each position of the text to the next.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Recomputing the hash function from scratch at each position would be too slow.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Lines 2, 4, and 6 each require O(*m*) time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] However, line 2 is only executed once, and line 6 is only executed if the hash values match, which is unlikely to happen more than a few times.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Line 5 is executed O(*n*) times, but each comparison only requires constant time, so its impact is O(*n*).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Naively computing the hash value for the substring `s[i+1..i+m]` requires O(*m*) time because each character is examined.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Since the hash computation is done on each loop, the algorithm with a naive hash computation requires O(*mn*) time, the same complexity as a straightforward string matching algorithm.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] For speed, the hash must be computed in constant time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The trick is the variable `hs` already contains the previous hash value of `s[i..i+m-1]`.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] If that value can be used to compute the next hash value in constant time, then computing successive hash values will be fast.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The trick can be exploited using a rolling hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] A rolling hash is a hash function specially designed to enable this operation.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] A trivial (but not very good) rolling hash function just adds the values of each character in the substring.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] This simple function works, but will result in statement 5 being executed more often than other more sophisticated rolling hash functions such as those discussed in the next section.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Good performance requires a good hashing function for the encountered data.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] If the hashing is poor (such as producing the same hash value for every input), then line 6 would be executed O(*n*) times (i.e. on every iteration of the loop).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Because character-by-character comparison of strings with length *m* takes O(*m*) time, the whole algorithm then takes a worst-case O(*mn*) time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The key to the Rabin–Karp algorithm's performance is the efficient computation of hash values of the successive substrings of the text.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin fingerprint is a popular and effective rolling hash function.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The hash function described here is not a Rabin fingerprint, but it works equally well.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] It treats every substring as a number in some base, the base being usually the size of the character set.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Technically, this algorithm is only similar to the true number in a non-decimal system representation, since for example we could have the "base" less than one of the "digits".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] See hash function for a much more detailed discussion.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The essential benefit achieved by using a rolling hash such as the Rabin fingerprint is that it is possible to compute the hash value of the next substring from the previous one by doing only a constant number of operations, independent of the substrings' lengths.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] We can then compute the hash of the next substring, "bra", from the hash of "abr" by subtracting the number added for the first 'a' of "abr", i.e.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] 97 × 2562, multiplying by the base and adding for the last a of "bra", i.e.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] If the substrings in question are long, this algorithm achieves great savings compared with many other hashing schemes.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Theoretically, there exist other algorithms that could provide convenient recomputation, e.g. multiplying together ASCII values of all characters so that shifting substring would only entail dividing the previous hash by the first character value, then multiplying by the new last character's value.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The limitation, however, is the limited size of the integer data type and the necessity of using modular arithmetic to scale down the hash results.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Meanwhile, naive hash functions do not produce large numbers quickly, but, just like adding ASCII values, are likely to cause many hash collisions and hence slow down the algorithm.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] Hence the described hash function is typically the preferred one in the Rabin–Karp algorithm.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm is inferior for single pattern searching to Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm, Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and other faster single pattern string searching algorithms because of its slow worst case behavior.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] However, it is a useful algorithm for multiple pattern search.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] We assume all the substrings have a fixed length *m*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] A naïve way to search for *k* patterns is to repeat a single-pattern search taking O(*n*+*m*) time, totaling in O((*n*+*m*)*k*) time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rabin-karp-algorithm] In contrast, the above algorithm can find all *k* patterns in O(*n*+*km*) expected time, assuming that a hash table check works in O(1) expected time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] A **rolling hash** (also known as recursive hashing or rolling checksum) is a hash function where the input is hashed in a window that moves through the input.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] One of the main applications is the Rabin–Karp string search algorithm, which uses the rolling hash described below.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Another popular application is the rsync program, which uses a checksum based on Mark Adler's adler-32 as its rolling hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Low Bandwidth Network Filesystem (LBFS) uses a Rabin fingerprint as its rolling hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] FastCDC (Fast Content-Defined Chunking) uses a compute-efficient Gear fingerprint as its rolling hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] At best, rolling hash values are pairwise independent or strongly universal.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] They cannot be 3-wise independent, for example.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] where a is a constant, and $c_{1},...,c_{k}$ are the input characters (but this function is not a Rabin fingerprint, see below).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] In order to avoid manipulating huge H values, all math is done modulo n .
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The choice of a and n is critical to get good hashing; in particular, the modulus n is typically a prime number.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] See linear congruential generator for more discussion.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Removing and adding characters simply involves adding or subtracting the first or last term.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Shifting all characters by one position to the left requires multiplying the entire sum H by a .
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Shifting all characters by one position to the right requires dividing the entire sum H by a .
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Note that in modulo arithmetic, a can be chosen to have a multiplicative inverse $a^{-1}$ by which H can be multiplied to get the result of the division without actually performing a division.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The Rabin fingerprint is another hash, which also interprets the input as a polynomial, but over the Galois field GF(2).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Instead of seeing the input as a polynomial of bytes, it is seen as a polynomial of bits, and all arithmetic is done in GF(2) (similarly to CRC-32).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The hash is the remainder after the division of that polynomial by an irreducible polynomial over GF(2).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] It is possible to update a Rabin fingerprint using only the entering and the leaving byte, making it effectively a rolling hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Because it shares the same author as the Rabin–Karp string search algorithm, which is often explained with another, simpler rolling hash, and because this simpler rolling hash is also a polynomial, both rolling hashes are often mistaken for each other.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Hashing by cyclic polynomial—sometimes called Buzhash—is also simple and it has the benefit of avoiding multiplications, using circular shift instead.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] It is a form of tabulation hashing: it presumes that there is some substitution function s from characters to integers in the interval $[0,2^{L})$ , essentially a lookup table (each of the 32 bit-positions of the values of *s* should be balanced, i.e. have as many 1s as there are 0s).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Let the function $\operatorname {rol}$ be bitwise rotation.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Let $\oplus$ be the bitwise exclusive or.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Let $c_{i}$ be the i-th byte in a stream, and w be the window size in use.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] All values of *H* are within the interval $[0,2^{L})$ .
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The value of *H* is neither formally uniform nor 2-universal, despite its empirical uniformity.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] However, it can be made formally uniform and pairwise independent if only a consecutive $L-w+1$ bits are taken from the hash.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] In practice, this can be a bitwise AND (masking) operation: $H'_{i}=H_{i}\mathbin {\&} (1\ll (w-1)-1)$ , where $\mathbin {\&}$ is a bitwise AND and $\ll$ is a left-shift.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] In addition, the authors of borg note that *w* should not be a multiple of 2 *L* if a *seed* is used to modify *s[]* by XORing each value with the seed.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Gear chunking is another type of tabulation hashing.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Let *s* be an unchanging table of 256 random unsigned 32-bit integers, *H* be the hash accumulator (unsigned integer, at least 32 bits), and *f* be the file represented as an array of bytes (8-bit integers, 1-based subscript).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Compared to the cyclic polynomial hash, the left-rotate operation is replaced by left-shift, which removes the need to remove the contribution of an out-of-window byte.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Chunking is done based on the top bits of *H*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] This type of chunking generates results comparable with the Rabin fingerprint in one-third of the time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] However, in practice the distribution of split-sizes were wider than Rabin, making deduplication results about 1% poorer for the typical cases and 6% poor for the worst case.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Using the bottom bits is also acceptable but reduces the effective sliding-window size.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The largest effective size appears when the mask samples a number of non-consecutive bits from a relatively wide "span" of *H*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] One of the interesting use cases of the rolling hash function is that it can create dynamic, content-based chunks of a stream or file.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] This is especially useful when it is required to send only the changed chunks of a large file over a network: a simple byte addition at the front of the file would normally cause all fixed size windows to become updated, while in reality, only the first "chunk" has been modified.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Each chunk will thus have an average size of ${\textstyle 2^{n}}$ bytes.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] This approach ensures that unmodified data (more than a window size away from the changes) will have the same boundaries.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Once the boundaries are known, the chunks need to be compared by cryptographic hash value to detect changes.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Such content-defined chunking (CDC) or content-based chunking (CBC) is often used for data deduplication.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The hash function used can be any rolling-hash algorithm.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Content-based chunking has the advantage that in *most* cases, local changes to a file only affects the chunk it is in and possibly the next chunk, but no other chunk.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Different choices of algorithms and hashes offer different strengths of this guarantee.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Shifting the window by one byte simply involves adding the new character to the sum and subtracting the oldest character (no longer in the window) from the sum.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Because of the properties of modulo arithmetic, the storage required is only 12 bits.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] For every n where $H(n)==0$ , these programs cut the file between n and $n+1$ .
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] FastCDC optimizes Gear-based CDC mainly by adding a "kickstart" loop for bytes before the desired minimal size.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] By skipping the check for cutting, performance is improved while also adding a feature that allows for controlling the minimum size.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The new scheme approximately doubles the speed over the olg Gear-based algorithm and is 10× as fast as the Rabin-based CDC approach.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] Where the *Gear* array is equivalent to the *s* table above.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] An advanced version uses two different masks derived from the above *Mask*, one with 15 set bits and the other with 11 set bits.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] The former is used when *i* < 8 KB; afterwards the latter takes over.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] This tightens the chunk-size distribution around the desired average and improves deduplication.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] All rolling hash functions can be computed in linear time for the number of characters and updated in constant time when characters are shifted by one position.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/rolling-hash] In particular, computing the Rabin–Karp rolling hash of a string of length k requires $O(k)$ modular arithmetic operations, and hashing by cyclic polynomials requires $O(k)$ bitwise exclusive ors and circular shifts.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] A **string-searching algorithm**, sometimes called **string-matching algorithm**, is an algorithm that searches a body of text for portions that match by pattern.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In practice, the method of feasible string-search algorithm may be affected by the string encoding.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In particular, if a variable-width encoding is in use, then it may be slower to find the *N*th character, perhaps requiring time proportional to *N*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] This may significantly slow some search algorithms.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] One of many possible solutions is to search for the sequence of code units instead, but doing so may produce false matches unless the encoding is specifically designed to avoid it.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The most basic case of string searching involves one (often very long) string, sometimes called the *haystack*, and one (often very short) string, sometimes called the *needle*.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The goal is to find one or more occurrences of the needle within the haystack.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] One might request the first occurrence of "to", which is the fourth word; or all occurrences, of which there are 3; or the last, which is the fifth word from the end.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Very commonly, however, various constraints are added.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might want to match the "needle" only where it consists of one (or more) complete words—perhaps defined as *not* having other letters immediately adjacent on either side.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In that case a search for "hew" or "low" should fail for the example sentence above, even though those literal strings do occur.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Another common example involves "normalization".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Finally, for strings that represent natural language, aspects of the language itself become involved.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might wish to find all occurrences of a "word" despite it having alternate spellings, prefixes or suffixes, etc.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Another more complex type of search is regular expression searching, where the user constructs a pattern of characters or other symbols, and any match to the pattern should fulfill the search.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] where the "?" conventionally makes the preceding character ("u") optional.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] This article mainly discusses algorithms for the simpler kinds of string searching.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] A similar problem introduced in the field of bioinformatics and genomics is the maximal exact matching (MEM).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Given two strings, MEMs are common substrings that cannot be extended left or right without causing a mismatch.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] A simple and inefficient way to see where one string occurs inside another is to check at each index, one by one.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] First, we see if there is a copy of the needle starting at the first character of the haystack; if not, we look to see if there's a copy of the needle starting at the second character of the haystack, and so forth.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In this approach, backtracking is avoided by constructing a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that recognizes a stored search string.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] These are expensive to construct—they are usually created using the powerset construction—but are very quick to use.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For example, the DFA shown to the right recognizes the word "MOMMY".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] This approach is frequently generalized in practice to search for arbitrary regular expressions.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Knuth–Morris–Pratt computes a DFA that recognizes inputs with the string to search for as a suffix, Boyer–Moore starts searching from the end of the needle, so it can usually jump ahead a whole needle-length at each step.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Baeza–Yates keeps track of whether the previous *j* characters were a prefix of the search string, and is therefore adaptable to fuzzy string searching.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The bitap algorithm is an application of Baeza–Yates' approach.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Faster search algorithms preprocess the text.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] After building a substring index, for example a suffix tree or suffix array, the occurrences of a pattern can be found quickly.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] As an example, a suffix tree can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, and all z occurrences of a pattern can be found in $O(m)$ time under the assumption that the alphabet has a constant size and all inner nodes in the suffix tree know what leaves are underneath them.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The latter can be accomplished by running a DFS algorithm from the root of the suffix tree.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Some search methods, for instance trigram search, are intended to find a "closeness" score between the search string and the text rather than a "match/non-match".
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] These are sometimes called "fuzzy" searches.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The various algorithms can be classified by the number of patterns each uses.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *m* is the length of the pattern, *n* the length of the searchable text, and *k* = |Σ| is the size of the alphabet.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** has been the standard benchmark for the practical string-search literature.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *M* is the length of the longest pattern, *m* their total length, *n* the length of the searchable text, *o* the number of occurrences.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Naturally, the patterns can not be enumerated finitely in this case.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] They are represented usually by a regular grammar or regular expression.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Other classification approaches are possible.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] One of the most common uses preprocessing as main criteria.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In real-time string matching, one requires the matcher to output a response after reading each character of the text, that indicates whether this is the last character of a match.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] The response has to be given within constant time.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] For the more lenient version, if one does not mind that the preprocessing time and memory requirement dependend on the size of the alphabet, a real-time solution is provided by automaton matching.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Zvi Galil developed a method to turn certain algorithms into real-time algorithms, and applied it to produce a variant of the KMP matcher that runs in real time under the strict requirement.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In this version of the string searching problem, there is a special symbol, ø (read: don't care), which can match any other symbol (including another ø).
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Don't care symbols can appear either in the pattern or in the text.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] In 2002, an algorithm for this problem that runs in $O(n\log m)$ time has been given by Richard Cole and Ramesh Hariharan, improving on a solution from 1973 by Fischer and Paterson that has complexity $O(n\log m\log k)$ , where *k* is the size of the alphabet.
[src:rabin-karp-algorithm/string-searching-algorithm] Another algorithm, claimed simpler, has been proposed by Clifford and Clifford.
